An '''anatopism''' (from the [[Greek language|Greek]] ''ana'', "against," and ''topos'', "place") is something that is out of its proper place.  Thus, for example, an [[outrigger canoe]] would be an anatopism in [[ancient Rome]].

===Anatopism in literature===
The [[Poland|Polish]] writer [[Bolesław Prus]], for the sake of making a point, introduces into chapter 63 of his [[historical novel]] ''[[Pharaoh (novel)|Pharaoh]]'', set in the [[ancient Egypt|ancient ''Egypt'']] of 1085 B.C.E., a substance that behaves like [[gunpowder]]; this is an anatopism, since gunpowder was invented in ''[[China]]''.  Another apparent anatopism introduced by the author (in chapter 45) is something resembling a [[telescope]], which may also be an ''[[anachronism]]''.

